Detection of eDNA

knitr::include_graphics("fig/ddPCR.png")

ddPCR estimation of concentration

  • A volume \(V_S\) of water is collected, and all of the eDNA it contains is collected by filtration. Assume a count \(N_j\) of eDNA fragments of type \(j\) is collected (\(j=1,\ldots,J\)). If the number density of fragments in the water is \(\nu_j\) then \[ N_j | \nu_j, V_S \sim \text{Poisson}(\nu_jV_S) \]
  • The collected eDNA is mixed with a volume \(V_M\) of a proprietary mix of primers, probes and water;
  • A test volume \(V_T\) (\(1\mu\ell\)) is taken from the mixture: The count of fragments in the test volume is \[ n_j | N_j,V_M,V_T\sim\text{Poisson}(N_jV_T/V_M) \]
  • The test volume is atomised into \(m\) droplets. The count of fragments in droplet \(i\) is \[ y_{ji} | n_j,m \sim\text{Poisson}(n_j/m) \]
  • The probability that droplet \(i\) has zero fragments is \[ \Pr(y_{ji}=0 | n_j,m) = \exp\left(-\frac{n_j}{m}\right) \] and thus the probability that it contains any fragments is \[ \Pr(y_{ji}>0 | n_j,m) = 1-\exp\left(-\frac{n_j}{m}\right) \]
  • The eDNA in the droplets is amplified by PCR, and \(m_{j+}\) of the droplets are observed to be positive for fragment type \(j\). Thus the observed proportion of positive droplets is \[ \widehat{p}_+ = \frac{m_{j+}}{m} \] and \[ m_{j+} | n_j,m \sim \text{Binomial}\left(m,1-e^{-n_j/m}\right) \] or if \(n_j/m\) is very small then \[ m_{j+} | n_j,m \sim \text{Poisson}\left(m\left(1-e^{-n_j/m}\right)\right) \] Note that we assume no false positives and no false negatives when individual droplets are amplified and tested for the presence of the eDNA.

This process is aimed at determining \(\nu_j\), the original number density in the water from which the sample was collected. A simple estimate of \(\nu_j\) is \[ \widehat{\nu}_j = -\frac{V_M m}{V_SV_T} \log\left(1-\frac{m_{j+}}{m}\right) \] However in this application we are most interested in the probability that the process leads to negative result when \(\nu_j\) is non-zero. i.e. we want to know \[\begin{eqnarray} && \mbox{}\hspace{-2cm}\Pr(m_{j+}=0 | m,V_S,V_T,V_M,\nu_j)\\ &=& \sum_{N_j=0}^\infty \sum_{n_j=0}^\infty \Pr(m_{j+}=0 | n_j,m) \Pr(n_j | N_j,V_M,V_T) \Pr(N_j | \nu_j,V_S)\\ &=& \sum_{N_j=0}^\infty \sum_{n_j=0}^\infty \exp\left(-m\left[1-e^{-n_j/m}\right]\right) \exp\left(-\frac{N_jV_T}{V_M}\right)\frac{\left(\frac{N_jV_T}{V_M}\right)^{n_j}}{n_j!} \exp\left(-\nu_jV_S\right)\frac{\left(\nu_jV_S\right)^{N_j}}{N_j!} \end{eqnarray}\] Note that the sum over \(n_j\) should only be from 0 to \(N_j\), but we sum to infinity because the additional terms are all negligible.

Writing the ratio \(V_T/V_M\), i.e. the proportion of the mixture that is atomised and tested, as \(d\), and suppressing the index \(j\) \[\begin{eqnarray} && \mbox{}\hspace{-2cm}\Pr(m_{+}=0 | m,V_S,d,\nu)\\ &=& \sum_{N=0}^\infty \sum_{n=0}^\infty \Pr(m_{+}=0 | n,m) \Pr(n | N,d) \Pr(N | \nu,V_S)\\ &=& \sum_{N=0}^\infty \sum_{n=0}^\infty \exp\left(-m\left[1-e^{-n/m}\right]\right) e^{-Nd}\frac{(Nd)^{n}}{n!} e^{-\nu V_S}\frac{(\nu V_S)^{N}}{N!} \end{eqnarray}\]

At very low concentrations \[ n | \nu, V_S, d \sim \text{Poisson}(\nu V_Sd) \] so that \[\begin{eqnarray} && \mbox{}\hspace{-2cm}\Pr(m_{+}=0 | m,V_S,d,\nu)\\ &=& \sum_{n=0}^\infty \Pr(m_{+}=0 | n,m) \Pr(n | \nu,V_S,d)\\ &=& \sum_{n=0}^\infty \exp\left(-m\left[1-e^{-n/m}\right]\right) e^{-\nu V_S d}\frac{(\nu V_S d)^{n}}{n!}\\ &=& \sum_{n=0}^\infty \exp\left(-m\left[1-e^{-n/m}\right]\right) e^{-\lambda}\frac{\lambda^{n}}{n!}\\ \end{eqnarray}\] where \(\lambda = \nu V_S d\).

Typically we have \(m=2\times10^4\) droplets. We might expect \(\nu V_s\simeq 10\) fragments to be catpured, and a subsampling of \(d=1/20\), and in that case \(\lambda\simeq 0.5\)

probmp0 <- function(lambda, m=20000, nbig=20000) {
  nvec <- 0:nbig
  fval <- sapply(lambda, function(lambdav) sum(exp(-m*(1-exp(-nvec/m)))*dpois(nvec,lambdav)))
  return(fval)
}
m <- 20000; nbig <- m
np <- 101
lambdavec <- 10^(seq(from=-3,to=+1,length=np))
plot(lambdavec, (probmp0(lambdavec, m=m, nbig=nbig)), type="l",
     xlab=expression(lambda), ylab=expression("Pr("*m["+"]==0*"): Prob of no detections"), 
     main=bquote(lambda==nu*V[S]*d*";  "*m*"="*.(m)*" droplets"))

Particle dispersal

If there is a mass released at time \(t_0\) at location \({\bf x}_0\) then it is transported by advection (water flow) and dispersion (turbulence).

Let \(p({\bf x},t | {\bf x}_0, t_0, {\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\) be the proportion of the mass released that is found at location \({\bf x}\) at time \(t\), given water flow \({\bf v}()\) and dispersion \({\bf a}()\). \(\Psi\) is a set of additional parameters controlling the flow/dispersion model.

A simple model is a simple Gaussian spread in 2D: \[\begin{eqnarray} p({\bf x},t | {\bf x}_0, t_0, {\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi) &=& \frac{I(t-t_0\geq 0)}{2\pi \sqrt{a_xa_y}(t-t_0+t_\varepsilon)} \exp\left( -\frac{\left(x-x_0-v_x(t-t_0)\right)^2}{2a_x(t-t_0+t_\varepsilon)} -\frac{\left(y-y_0-v_y(t-t_0)\right)^2}{2a_y(t-t_0+t_\varepsilon)} \right)\\ &=& g({\bf x},t-t_0 |{\bf x}_0, {\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi) \end{eqnarray}\] where a small positive temporal offset \(\Psi=\{t_\varepsilon\}\) is added to avoid a singularity at \(t=t_0\).

We have \[ \int\!\!\int p({\bf x},t|{\bf x}_0,t_0, {\bf v},{\bf a}, \Psi) \,{\rm d}{\bf x}= 1 \] for all times \(t>t_0\).

Note that \(g()\) has a symmetry in which we can interchange \({\bf x}\) and \({\bf x}_0\) and at the same time reverse the velocity field, so for any time interval \(u\geq 0\): \[\begin{equation} g({\bf x},u|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v},{\bf a},\Psi) = g({\bf x}_0,u|{\bf x},-{\bf v},{\bf a},\Psi) \end{equation}\]

source("funcs.R")
nx <- 101

y0 <- mean(c(ymin,ymax))
t0 <- 0
vx <- 5; vy <- 1
ax <- 2^2; ay <- 4^2
teps <- 0.01

A simple backtracking model simply reverses the flow field. If we are interested in the likely origin of mass observed at location \({\bf x}_1\) at time \(t_1\) we can backtrack by reversing \({\bf v}()\).

We might assume that the likelihood that the observed mass was released at location \({\bf x}\) at time \(t<t_1\) is given by \[\begin{eqnarray} \tilde{p}({\bf x},t | {\bf x}_1,t_1, {\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi) &=& g({\bf x},t_1-t |{\bf x}_1, -{\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\\ &=& p({\bf x},-t | {\bf x}_1,-t_1, -{\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi) \end{eqnarray}\] In the simple Gaussian model above this is \[\begin{eqnarray} &&\mbox{}\hspace{-2cm}\tilde{p}({\bf x},t | {\bf x}_1, t_1, {\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\\ &=& p({\bf x},t_1 | {\bf x}_1, t, -{\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\\ &=& p({\bf x},-t | {\bf x}_1, -t_1, -{\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\\ &=& g({\bf x},t_1-t | {\bf x}_1, -{\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\\ &=& \frac{I(t_1-t\geq 0)}{2\pi\sqrt{a_xa_y}(t_1-t+t_\varepsilon)} \exp\left( -\frac{\left(x-x_1+v_x(t_1-t)\right)^2}{2a_x(t_1-t+t_\varepsilon)} -\frac{\left(y-y_1+v_y(t_1-t)\right)^2}{2a_y(t_1-t+t_\varepsilon)} \right) \end{eqnarray}\]

Back tracking: \(\tilde{p}({\bf x},t|{\bf x}_1,t_1, {\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi) = p({\bf x},-t|{\bf x}_1,-t_1, -{\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi)\): \(t_1, \ldots, t_1-10\) (no decay)

Continuous release with decay

Assume that at location \({\bf x}_0\) there is a continuous release of mass at a rate \(N_0\) kg/s. Further assume that the mass decays at a rate \[ d(t|T_h,T_m) = 2^{-t/T_h} I(0\leq t\leq T_m) \] where \(T_h\) is the decay half life and \(T_m\) is the maximum age at which all particles have disintegrated. If we set \(\lambda = (1/T_h)\log 2\) then \[ d(t|T_h,T_m) = e^{-\lambda t} I(0\leq t\leq T_m) \] The steady state mass in the system is then \[\begin{eqnarray} M_0 &=& \int_{-\infty}^t N_0 d(t-t_0|T_h,T_m)\;{\rm d}t_0\\ &=& N_0 \int_{-\infty}^t e^{-\lambda(t-t_0)} I(t_0>t-T_m)\;{\rm d}t_0\\ &=& N_0 \int_{t-T_m}^t e^{-\lambda(t-t_0)} \;{\rm d}t_0\\ &=& N_0 \int_0^{T_m} e^{-\lambda u} \;{\rm d}u\\ &=& \frac{N_0}{\lambda}\left[1-e^{-\lambda T_m}\right]\\ &=&\frac{N_0T_h}{\log 2}\left[1-e^{-\lambda T_m}\right] \end{eqnarray}\]

The mass density transiting per unit time at location \({\bf x}\) at time \(t\) emitted from a point source at \({\bf x}_0\) at time \(t_0\) is \[ \frac{{\rm d}\rho({\bf x},t|N_0,{\bf x}_0,t_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(), \Psi)}{{\rm d}t} = N_0 d(t-t_0|T_h,T_m) p({\bf x},t|{\bf x}_0,t_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi) \]

Density rate \({\rm d}\rho({\bf x},t|N_0,{\bf x}_0,t_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(), \Psi)/{\rm d}t\), \(t=t_0, \ldots, t_0+10\) (with decay). (Scales differ between panels: note max and sum values.)

par(mfrow=c(3,4))
par(mar=0.1*c(1,1,1,1))
n0 <- 1
th <- 5
tm <- 7

   amat <- outer(xvec,yvec, denratefunc, t=t,
                 x0=x0,y0=y0,t0=0, vx=vx,vy=vy, ax=ax,ay=ay, teps=teps, n0=n0,th=th,tm=tm)
   #amat <- log(1+amat)
   #if(t==0) {
   #   amin <- min(amat)
   #   amax <- max(amat)
   #}

   amax <- max(amat)
   breaks <- seq(from=amin, to=amax, length=length(colvec)+1)
   image(xvec, yvec, amat, asp=1, col=colvec, breaks=breaks, axes=FALSE)
   #image(xvec, yvec, amat,asp=1, main=bquote("Forwards with decay:" ~ t==.(t)), xlab="x", ylab="y",
   #      col=colvec, breaks=breaks)
   mtext(bquote("sum:"~.(sum(amat))~"max:"~.(max(amat))), side=3, adj=1, cex=0.6, line=-1, col="white")

The total (equilibrium) mass density present is \[\begin{eqnarray} &&\mbox{}\hspace{-2cm}\rho({\bf x},t|N_0,{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi)\\ &=& \rho({\bf x}|N_0,{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi)\\ &=& \int_{-\infty}^t N_0 d(t-t_0|T_h,T_m) p({\bf x},t|{\bf x}_0,t_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi)\;{\rm d}t_0\\ &=& N_0 \int_{t-T_m}^t e^{-\lambda (t-t_0)} g({\bf x},t-t_0|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi)\;{\rm d}t_0\\ &=& N_0 \int_0^{T_m} e^{-\lambda u} g({\bf x},u|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi)\;{\rm d}u\\ &=& N_0 h({\bf x}|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi) \end{eqnarray}\] where \[ h({\bf x}|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi) = \int_0^{T_m} e^{-\lambda u} g({\bf x},u|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi)\;{\rm d}u \] The function \(h()\) retains the same symmetry as \(g()\), so since \[ g({\bf x},u|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v},{\bf a},\Psi) = g({\bf x}_0,u|{\bf x},-{\bf v},{\bf a},\Psi) \] it follows that \[ h({\bf x},u|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v},{\bf a},\Psi) = h({\bf x}_0,u|{\bf x},-{\bf v},{\bf a},\Psi) \]

In the Gaussian dispersal example \[ h({\bf x}|{\bf x}_0,{\bf v}(),{\bf a}(),\Psi) = \frac{1}{2\pi \sqrt{a_xa_y}} \int_0^{T_m} \frac{e^{-\lambda u}}{u+t_\varepsilon} \exp\left( -\frac{\left(x-x_0-v_xu\right)^2}{2a_x(u+t_\varepsilon)} -\frac{\left(y-y_0-v_yu\right)^2}{2a_y(u+,t_\varepsilon)} \right) \]

The above figure plots, for a continuous fixed source of rate \(N_0\) at location \({\bf x}_0\), the equilibrium density at all locations \({\bf x}\): \(N_0 h({\bf x}|{\bf x}_0)\).

Now plot at each \({\bf x}_0\) the equilibrium density at \({\bf x}_1\) (in the centre of the diagram) that would result from a continuous source at \({\bf x}_0\). i.e. \(N_0 h({\bf x}_1|{\bf x_0})\) \[\begin{eqnarray*} N_0 \tilde{h}({\bf x}_0 | {\bf x}_1, {\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi) &=& N_0 h({\bf x}_1|{\bf x}_0, {\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi)\\ &=& N_0 h({\bf x}_0|{\bf x}_1, -{\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi) \end{eqnarray*}\]

\(N_0 \tilde{h}({\bf x}_0|{\bf x}_!, {\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi) = N_0 h({\bf x}_1|{\bf x}_0, {\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi) = N_0 h({\bf x}_0|{\bf x}_1, -{\bf v}, {\bf a}, \Psi)\)

Probabilistic Inversion

Now assume that at some location \({\bf x}_1\) we observe a density \(\rho_1\), and that this in an observation made with error: \[ \rho_1 | \rho_1^\ast, \sigma_e \sim N(\rho_1^\ast, \sigma_e^2) \] were the true density is \(\rho_1^\ast\) and the error variance is \(\sigma_e^2\).

Assume that there is a single continous source of unknown strength \(N_0\) and unknown location \({\bf x}_0\). Priors for the strength and location are \(\pi(N_0)\) and \(\pi({\bf x}_0)\) respectively.

Assume that the velocity field \({\bf v}()\) and the diffusion field \({\bf a}()\) are known.

Using the results from the previous section, conditional on \(N_0\) and \({\bf x}_0\) the observed density at \({\bf x}_1\) is \[ \rho_1^\ast= N_0 h({\bf x}_1|{\bf x}_0, {\bf v}(), {\bf a}(), \Psi) \] which we write for brevity as \[ \rho_1^\ast = h_1^\ast({\bf x}_0) = h_1^\ast \] but noting its dependence on \({\bf x}_0\).

It follows that the joint distribution of the unknown source strength \(N_0\) and location \({\bf x}_0\) is \[\begin{eqnarray*} p(N_0,{\bf x}_0|\rho_1,{\bf x}_1) &\propto& \pi(N_0) \pi({\bf x}_0) \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2\sigma_e^2} \left[\rho_1-N_0h_1^\ast({\bf x}_0)\right]^2\right)\\ &\propto& \pi(N_0) \pi({\bf x}_0) \exp\left(-\frac{(h_1^\ast)^2}{2\sigma_e^2} \left[N_0-\frac{\rho_1}{h_1^\ast}\right]^2\right) \end{eqnarray*}\] A suitable prior for \(N_0\) is the Exponential(\(\mu\)) distribution \[\begin{eqnarray*} N_0 &\sim& \text{Exp}(\mu)\\ \pi(N_0) &=& \mu e^{-\mu N_0} \end{eqnarray*}\] This can be marginalised out of the posterior distribution as follows. Firstly the joint distribution is \[\begin{eqnarray*} p(N_0,{\bf x}_0|\rho_1,{\bf x}_1) &\propto& \pi({\bf x}_0) e^{-\mu N_0} \exp\left(-\frac{(h_1^\ast)^2}{2\sigma_e^2} \left[N_0-\frac{\rho_1}{h_1^\ast}\right]^2\right)\\ &\propto& \pi({\bf x}_0) \exp\left( -\frac{(h_1^\ast)^2}{2\sigma_e^2} \left[N_0-\left(\frac{\rho_1}{h_1^\ast} - \frac{\mu\sigma_e^2}{(h_1^\ast)^2} \right)\right]^2 - \frac{\rho_1\mu}{h_1^\ast} + \frac{\mu^2\sigma_e^2}{2(h_1^\ast)^2} \right) \end{eqnarray*}\] Integrating out \(N_0\) leads to \[\begin{eqnarray*} p({\bf x}_0|\rho_1,{\bf x}_1) &\propto& \pi({\bf x}_0) \frac{\sigma_e}{h_1^\ast} \exp\left( - \frac{\rho_1\mu}{h_1^\ast} + \frac{\mu^2\sigma_e^2}{2(h_1^\ast)^2} \right) \end{eqnarray*}\] If we let \(\sigma_e\rightarrow 0\) (indicating very accurate observations) we are left with a very simple form for the posterior: \[\begin{eqnarray*} p({\bf x}_0|\rho_1,{\bf x}_1) &\propto& \pi({\bf x}_0) \frac{1}{h_1^\ast} e^{\frac{\rho_1\mu}{h_1^\ast}} \end{eqnarray*}\] which we plot below for a uniform prior on the source location \(\pi({\bf x}_0)\propto 1\).

th <- 5
tm <- 7
ax <- 2^2; ay <- 5^2
x1 <- 50; y1 <- 50
rho1 <- 1; mu <- 1
amat <- n0*outer(xvec,yvec, hfunc,
                 x0=x1,y0=y1, vx=-vx,vy=-vy, ax=ax,ay=ay, teps=teps, th=th,tm=tm)

      main=bquote(p(x[0]*"|"*x[1])*":" ~ x[1]==(.(x0)*","*.(y0)) ~ "," ~ t[h]==.(th) ~ "," ~ t[m]==.(tm)), 
      xlab=expression(x[0]), ylab=expression(y[0]), col=colvec)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
image(xvec, yvec, qmat, asp=1, 
      main=bquote(p(x[0]*"|"*x[1])*":"  ~ pi(x[0]) %prop% 1), 
      xlab=expression(x[0]), ylab=expression(y[0]), col=colvec)
image(xvec, yvec, p0mat*qmat, asp=1, 
      main=bquote(p(x[0]*"|"*x[1])*":" ~ pi(x[0]) %prop% N[y](.(ya),.(sigmaa)^2)), 
      xlab=expression(x[0]), ylab=expression(y[0]), col=colvec)
